The Cascade 

As explained in  the dynamics of this gauge theory is extremely
rich.  Under the RG flow alternatively the gauge coupling of one of
the two gauge groups will go to strong coupling, and the theory will
undergo a Seiberg-duality .  There is also another version of
description of this duality, discussed in  which one keeps the
adjoint fields and the cascade is described as an affine Weyl
reflection.  This description of the duality can be immediately
implemented in the matrix model. We will discuss this later in the
context of matrix model.  Here we will review the Seiberg duality as
applied to this case in .

Suppose that  and that the gauge group  becomes
strongly coupled as we go towards the IR. So we will perform a Seiberg
duality with  colors and  flavors.  The duality will then
replace the strongly coupled gauge group as



and replace the bifundamentals  by new bifundamentals
. Apriori there is no relation between these fields.
Furthermore there are new meson fields



where we have contracted the  indices. So the mesons 
are neutral with respect to  but transform as adjoints under
the 'flavor gauge group' . There is further a tree-level
superpotential



(Here  indices are raised and lowered using ).
Plugging in these fields in
the original Klebanov-Witten superpotential  gives



It is imple to integrate out the meson fields, that only appear quadratically.
After a shift



we obtain the dual superpotential



This is the same quartic superpotential now written in terms of the
new bifundamentals for the  gauge theory.

We now want to see what happens to this argument when we have
deformations of  by arbitrary monomials in the 




Let us keep the variation of  infinitesimal. That is, we will be
interested in computing correlation function of chiral operators in
the undeformed theory with the couplings . In
this case the cascade goes through and we get the desired result by
replacing the monomials in terms of the meson fields and then
eliminating meson fields.

So, for example, in this way the operator  gets replaced
by . One then has to eliminate the meson fields using
the above superpotential. To leading order the equations for the
elimination of meson fields do not get modified, and we can simply replace



This means that we have the same set of chiral fields, but now written
in terms of the new bifundamentals . The same chiral operator
now takes the form . But beyond the leading order in
the couplings , it does change the basis of chiral fields. This
implies that in the process of the Seiberg duality we will have
operator mixing among the chiral fields.



A particular interesting case appears if we start with a gauge theory
with rank



If we apply the duality to this case, we are left with a pure 
gauge theory. The other gauge factor has disappeared.  So there are no
longer new bifundamental fields . The only dynamical fields
are the mesons  that we recall transform as adjoints under the
remaining gauge group . This critical case with  is
more subtle, since there are now baryon degrees of freedom, and a
well-known quantum correction to the moduli space.  Ignoring these
effects, the superpotential for this model, including arbitrary
deformations will be of the form


W = (M_11  M_22  - M_12  M_21  + f(M_ij ))
 

with  an arbitrary function of the four meson fields .  We
will see in a moment how, using the relation of F-term computations in
gauge theory to matrix models, this suggests a four-matrix model for
this  gauge theory with four adjoint chiral fields.

Clearly, in the connection with the  string we want to identify
the mesons fields  with the space-time coordinates  of
the conifold, and relate the superpotential deformation  to the
deformed conifold .  Note also that the cascade at the level of
gauge theory has been interpreted as flops in  and thus at
the topological level (i.e.  the theory on topological branes)
the cascade continues to hold for the matrix model.

