Stability of The Glueball Superpotential and K-Theory 

The above ideas are relevant for the resolution of the following
puzzle: If we fix a gauge group of finite rank , the powers of the
glueball superfield , defined as a fermion bilinear, terminate at
finite order, if we consider  as a classical field. How can one
then justify the perturbative computations of the glueball
superpotential, as was done successfully in  not incorporating
this fact?  One resolution of this is to use the "replica trick" and
embed the  theory in the  theory, and do the computation
in that context in the limit where  is large.  But under this
transformation the superpotential changes by a factor of , and so
in particular one is dealing with a different effective
theory. Moreover, one will have to argue why going back to the 
theory is as simple as dividing the superpotential by a factor of .

We feel a better resolution of this puzzle is what we have observed
here: The F-term of the supersymmetric gauge theory is equivalent  to that of a bigger gauge theory by an inverse cascade
effect.  This, as we have explained above, is related to adding 
extra brane/anti-brane pairs to an  theory with an
equivalent F-term content. In the context of this bigger gauge theory,
the computation of the glueball superpotential makes sense for higher
powers of  and , as long as we take  large enough.  In
fact we can take  without changing the F-terms of
the theory, and consider arbitrary powers of 's since the
ranks become infinite. This in particular justifies the perturbative
computation done in , without needing to change the F-term
content of the theory.

This is very similar to how K-theory captures D-brane charges, where
one considers adding an arbitrary number of brane/anti-brane pairs
.  We thus see a notion of "stability" of the perturbative
glueball superpotential computation, where one stabalizes the gauge
theory by adding sufficient numbers of branes and anti-branes so that
one can effectively ignore the condition that the glueball field 
is nilpotent classically.

Seiberg-like Dualities From Matrix Models 

Quiver theories with gauge group , consisting of adjoint
chiral field  on each node with some superpotential 
 and certain bifundamental fields , admit a duality
discovered in , considered in the context of affine A-D-E quiver
theories. We replace the rank of the gauge group at node  by the
sum of the adjacent ranks minus  (this is the analog of 
for Seiberg duality), and we replace


 and



where  denote the basis of positive roots associated to the nodes
of the affine quiver theory. This duality was interpreted in 
as a Weyl reflection on the node .  Exactly the same interpretation
can be done in the context of matrix model, which gives a derivation
of this duality; this point was already noted in  and we will
elaborate on it here.

The matrix model which describes the F-terms of this theory is the
quiver matrix model already studied in .
One can integrate out the bifundamental fields (as we did above for
the case of the ) to obtain the integral in term of the
eigenvalues of the  on each node:






This system is clearly invariant under the Weyl reflection.  To
make this more clear, consider the planar limit, where we associate
a density eigenvalue  to each node .  Then the
effective action can be written as






Viewing  and  as vectors and covectors in
the affine root lattice this system enjoys the natural Weyl reflection
action on each node, which leads to the duality mentioned above.  As
was noted in  this leads to a matrix model derivation of the
gauge theory dualityIn fact one can refine the statement of the
duality, as was done in , to explain how the critical points of
the matrix model (which correspond to arbitrary roots  of the
affine Dynkin diagram) get exchanged under the Weyl reflection. .

 Non-Critical Bosonic String and  Gauge Theory 

So far we have seen that a particular gauge theory, namely the affine
quiver theory based on  with quadratic superpotential,
has the same set of chiral fields as that of the  string at
self-dual radius. This is not accidental, as we will explain in this
section. Furthermore we give the detailed link between computations
of  correlation functions and F-terms of  supersymmetric
gauge theory. This will generalize the correspondence of the free
energies to arbitrary correlators.

It was argued in  (using the result of  describing  at
self-dual radius as a  Kazama-Suzuki model at level )
that B-model topological string theory on the deformed conifold
geometry



is equivalent to non-critical bosonic strings with  at self-dual
radius, where one identifies the geometry as the (complexified) ground
ring of the bosonic string theory. This identification was checked to
a few loop orders and extended to all loops using the results
. This identification was further studied in .

However, this topological model is equivalent (as a mirror of the duality
between Chern-Simons and topological strings ) to the resolved
conifold geometry with branes wrapping . In the connection
between the topological string and the type IIB string, these branes
get promoted to  branes, and in addition  branes, which are
points in the internal geometry. On the other hand the gauge theory of
this system involves the  quiver theory  already
discussed. Since the B-model topological string on the side including
branes computes -terms of the corresponding  gauge theory,
and that is equivalent to the matrix integral, we come to the
conclusion that the  non-critical bosonic string at self-dual
radius is equivalent to the  quiver matrix model. We
explain this identification now in more detail.

As discussed before for each observable of the  theory at self
dual radius, there is a chiral field in the matrix model and the gauge
theory, namely






