Using the cascade the associated gauge theory can also be viewed
as a single  gauge theory with 4 adjoint fields .
Ignoring the subtleties of baryons and the quantum moduli space, the
naive superpotential for the associated 4-matrix model is



In particular if we just deform the momentum modes of the 
self-dual string, i.e.  if we want to compute the scattering
amplitudes of the tachyon modes



two adjoint fields can be integrated out. So the correlations get
mapped to an  supersymmetric gauge theory with the
remaining two adjoints 



and with superpotential


W=X_+X_- +_n>0  t_n  X_+^n+t_-n   X_-^n.
 

This is exactly a well-known two-matrix model representation of the
 string .  Using the Harish Chandra-Itzykon-Zuber
integral, one can show that this matrix model is equivalent to another
model where one assumes that the matrices  commute. Since we
can also choose the reality condition , this is
sometimes also called the normal matrix modelA normal matrix 
satisfies . .

A generalization of this model that includes couplings  to the
winding modes or vortices  has been proposed in . In
this three-matrix model, one also introduces a unitary matrix 
that captures the vortices. The full action is


 X_+ X_- - UX_+ UX_-
+ _n>0  (t_+n  X_+^n + t_-n   X_-^n)
+ _k   _k U^k. 

It would be very interesting to relate this models directly to our
quiver model. (See in this respect also our comments in section 6.)


Generalizations 

The above example can be generalized in two basic directions. On the
one hand we can generalize this to the case where the radius of the
 circle is  times the self-dual radius. On the other hand, as
we discussed before, we can relax the condition of the adjoint
superpotential to be quadratic.  We will consider these two cases in
turn.

Multiples of The Self-Dual Radius 

The fastest way to obtain the matrix model and the gauge theory in
this case is to consider a  orbifold of the model with self-dual
radius - on the side of both the bosonic string, the matrix model,
the gauge theory and the geometry. Let us consider these in turn.

Recall that in the case of the non-critical  bosonic string at
