Deconstruction and  Quiver Matrix Model 

A particular limit of the model we have been studying is related to
the deconstruction of the six-dimensional  superconformal
theory . This is also an interesting limit from the point of view
of  theory. If we consider the uncompactified limit 
 which leads to  string on an infinite real line, then we
obtain the  quiver theory.  The infinite array of
nodes of the quiver is naturally identified as a deconstruction, or
discretization, of the  line.

Thus, if we consider the uncompactified  theory with all the
momentum fields (including the cosmological constant operator) turned
off, i.e.   for all nodes , and then turn off the
superpotential , we obtain the quiver theory
relevant for the deconstruction of the  SCFT in  .
The choice of setting  can be viewed as a
regularization of the  theory (freezing to particular points on
the scalar moduli space, similarly to what was done in  in getting
 information from the  deformation). The most natural
superpotential for the  at infinite radius is the quadratic
potential  which freezes  to zero. But we can also
deform away from this point by considering a more general ,
alternating in sign from one node to another, to freeze to an
arbitrary point in the  moduli space.  We can also deform the
 theory by having varying ranks on each node of the
 quiver. This gets mapped to the correlations of the
momentum states of  theory on an infinite line.  Given the vast
literature on correlations of the decompactified  string theory,
this should lead to new insights into  little strings, which is
worth further study.

Let us explain further why obtaining the deconstruction theory of
 superconformal theory is not unexpected. As was shown in
 the theory of D3 branes near a conifold
singularity is the same as the theory of D3 brane near an 
singularity where the  geometry is fibered over the plane (giving
rise to the superpotential ).  Orbifolding this by 
can be viewed as orbifolding the  singularity by  which is
the same as modding  by  producing an 
singularity. Thus the  branes in this geometry are the same as
what is used in the deconstruction of  SCFT. Moreover, after
deforming by the superpotential term, is the same as the theory we are
studying which is equivalent to  at  times the self-dual
radius.

Note also that the deconstruction of the  theory has
effectively allowed us to describe F-terms of this theory in terms of
a matrix model which is dual to the  (which in turn is related to
2d black hole geometry).  This throat region description is
reminiscent of holography in this context studied in
.  Here we are encountering this
directly from the gauge theory, which is equivalent in this context to
a matrix model.




Higher-Dimensional Field Theories 

In this section we want to point out an obvious generalization to
higher-dimensional field theories of the connection between
four-dimensional  gauge theories and matrix models.

10D Super-Yang-Mills and Holomorphic Chern-Simons 

Let us start with a characteristic example. Consider ten-dimensional
super Yang-Mills theory on a space-time of the form ,
with  a Calabi-Yau three-fold. We want to keep all the Kaluza-Klein
modes on the internal manifold , also the massive ones, and thus
consider this as a four-dimensional supersymmetric gauge theory with
an infinite number of fields. This field theory can be regarded as an
effective field theory, with some unspecified UV completion, or we can
discretize the model by deconstructing the extra dimensions. As such
the action can be written in terms of a   superspace
notation, using  bosonic coordinates  and the usual
4d spinor coordinates .

Written in this way the action will contain D-terms, that are
integrals over , and F-term, that are integrals over .
More precisely, for the  SYM theory the action takes the
following form , .  Choose complex coordinates
 for the internal space .  Similarly write the
internal components of the Yang-Mills gauge fields in terms of a
holomorphic connection  () and a conjugated
anti-holomorphic connection . Let  be the
spinor field strength of the four-dimensional gauge connection
. The fields  and  should be considered as 
infinite sets of four-dimensional chiral superfields, parametrized by
the internal coordinate .

The F-term of the action then takes the form , 



where the tree-level superpotential is given by


W_tree  = _Y d^6y  [
