We can now apply the philosophy of  to this model, considered
as a 4d  theory, and compute the effective superpotential in
terms of an auxiliary internal field theory given by the action
. So the matrix model of  is now replaced by the
six-dimensional holomorphic Chern-Simons gauge theory. This is of course
just a direct field theory derivation of the result of  that the
four-dimensional effective action of the type IIB open string is
computed in terms of the B-model topological open string on the
internal manifold. In this case the open string theory is given by a
collection of  D9 branes wrapped over the Calabi-Yau .

Perhaps we should spell out this connection a bit more precisely in
this case. Let  be the rank of the holomorphic Chern-Simons gauge
theory. (Again, just as in the case in 4 dimensions, we should be
careful not to confuse the rank of the gauge theory  and the rank of
the auxiliary topological theory .) Suppose that the manifold  is
such that there are  isolated critical points of the
superpotential, i.e.   inequivalent holomorphic connections
without moduli. Let  be the rank of these
connections.  Then we have a symmetry breaking pattern



and can consider the 't Hooft limit . This will then
lead in the usual way to  gaugino condensates .  The
4d effective superpotential is now again given by


W_eff  = _i (N_i_0 S_i  + _i S_i)
 

with  the planar partition function of the holomorphic CS field
theory.  Note that if we applied this to the case of ordinary CS
theory on  we obtain the embedding of the duality of CS with
topological string ,  into a direct 4d field theory
language (for another description of this field theory see ).

General Philosophy 

The example of 10d super Yang-Mills illustrates nicely the general
philosophy. Any -dimensional supersymmetric gauge theory can be
written in terms of 4d  superfields 
parametrized by coordinates  on an internal -dimensional
manifold . Such a theory will have a tree-level superpotential that
is given by some -dimensional bosonic  action



containing in general gauge fields and matter fields on . The 4d
effective superpotential  is now expressed through  in terms
of the effective action   of the internal -dimensional
bosonic gauge theory.



For classical groups and (bi)fundamental matter
this effective action is computed in terms of planar Feynman graphs of
the internal theory.

Many interesting cases can be studied in this way.  In the next
subsection we explain how 5-dimensional  supersymmetric gauge
theories can be deconstructed in this way, which leads us directly to
matrix quantum mechanics.


Deconstruction of 5D Gauge Theories and Matrix Quantum Mechanics 

Let us first consider deconstruction of a pure  Yang-Mills in 5
dimensions compactified on a circle of radius .  This
case has been recently studied in .  Viewed from
the perspective of  in 4 dimensions this has in addition a
chiral scalar field  given by the component of the gauge field
along the 5th direction.  (The extra (real) scalar field, that is part
of the 5-dimensional vector multiplet, complexifies .)  This scalar
gives rise to a holonomy



around the 5th circle of length .  Here  (whose
eigenvalues are periodic with period ) represents a flat
direction.

In terms of the general discussion of the previous section the internal
theory is here a one-dimensional gauge theory. Such a theory is
entirely described in terms of the holonomy  modulo conjugation by
. So we immediately see that according to the above philosophy
5d super Yang-Mills will be related to a unitary  matrix
model. If we break to  in 4 dimensions by choosing some
tree-level superpotential , the F-terms of this
deformed theory are computed by the large  limit of the
holomorphic gauged unitary matrix model




with  the Haar measure on .

